In the "DiscordBot" folder, run `npm init` to initiate a new Node.js project. This will create a package.json file that will help you manage your project's dependencies and settings.

**Step 4: Install Discord.js v14**

To install Discord.js v14, run `npm install discord.js@14` in the "DiscordBot" folder. This will add the Discord.js v14 package to your project's dependencies.

**Step 5: Set up a new bot application in the Discord developer portal**

To set up a new bot application in the Discord developer portal, visit the Discord developer portal and click on "New Application". Fill in the details and click "Create". This will generate a new bot application with a unique token.

**Step 6: Add a bot user to the application**

In the Discord developer portal, navigate to the "Bot" section and click "Add a bot user". This will add a new bot user to your application.

**Step 7: Grab the token for your bot**

In the Discord developer portal, navigate to the "Bot" section and click on the "Token" button. This will generate a new token for your bot.

**Step 8: Write code for a Discord bot using Discord.js v14**

Here's a simple code for a Discord bot using Discord.js v14:

```javascript
const Discord = require("discord.js@14");
const client = new Discord.Client({
  intents: ["GUILD_MESSAGES", "GUILD_MEMBERS", "GUILD_BANS"],
  token: "YOUR_TOKEN_HERE"
});

client.on("ready", () => {
  console.log("Bot is ready!");
});

client.on("message", (message) => {
  if (message.content === "ban") {
    message.member.ban();
  }
});

client.on("guildBanAdd", (guild, member) => {
  console.log(`${member.user.tag} was banned from ${guild.name}`);
});

client.login();
```

In this code, I've added a simple "ban" command that will ban the user who sent the message. I've also added an event listener for "guildBanAdd" to log the banned user and the guild they were banned from.

